The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Bhel profit rises 33%
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Bhel profit rises 33%
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, Oct. 29: Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd (Bhel), the state-run turbine maker, has reported a 33 per cent hike in net profit for the second quarter ended September 30 at Rs 1,142.28 crore against Rs 857.88 crore during the same period last fiscal.        
	With this kind of result, Bhel has maintained its track record of earning profits uninterruptedly for nearly four decades, a company official said.        
	Total income increased 25.7 per cent to Rs 8,328.41 crore from Rs 6,625.21 crore in the year-ago period. Revenue from power rose 28.3 percent to Rs 6,965.03 crore from Rs 5,428.32 crore, while revenue from industry sector grew 16.5 per cent to Rs 1,857.70 crore from Rs 1,595.42 crore a year ago.        
	During the first six months of this fiscal, net sales increased 21.17 per cent to Rs 14,808.1 crore from Rs 12,220.9 crore a year earlier.        
	The largest public sector engineering company, which is capable of delivering 15,000- mega-watt (MW) equipment per annum, is augmenting its capacity to 20,000MW.        
	The PSU firm faces intense competition from Chinese rivals, who are seeking overseas orders following a slowdown in their domestic market.         
	Shanghai Electric Group signed a $10-billion order with Reliance Power yesterday to supply equipment for several coal-based plants with a proposed capacity of 30,000MW.         
	With the highest-ever order-book position of Rs 154,000 crore at the end of the second quarter, the company expects to achieve robust growth in 2010-11 and beyond, Bhel officials said.        
	The equipment maker had orders worth Rs 126,000 crore a year earlier.         
	India has installed power generation capacity of 164,835MW, and the government aims to expand capacity to 286,756MW by March 2017.                                                                                                                                       
